  38     return hasattr(obj, attr) and callable(getattr(obj, attr))

  41 #
  42 # TODO(grun): Create a subclass of list that values(), getlist(), allitems(),
  43 # etc return that the user can manipulate directly to control the omdict()
  44 # object.
  45 #
  46 # For example, users should be able to do things like
  47 #
  48 #   omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11)])
  49 #   omd.values(1).append('sup')
  50 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,11), (1,'sup')]
  51 #   omd.values(1).remove(11)
  52 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,'sup')]
  53 #   omd.values(1).extend(['two', 'more'])
  54 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,'sup'), (1,'two'), (1,'more')]
  55 #
  56 # or
  57 #
  58 #   omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11)])
  59 #   omd.allitems().extend([(2,2), (2,22)])
  60 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,11), (2,2), (2,22)])
  61 #
  62 # or
  63 #
  64 #   omd = omdict()
  65 #   omd.values(1) = [1, 11]
  66 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,11)]
  67 #   omd.values(1) = list(map(lambda i: i * -10, omd.values(1)))
  68 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,-10), (1,-110)]
  69 #   omd.allitems() = filter(lambda (k,v): v > -100, omd.allitems())
  70 #   omd.allitems() == [(1,-10)]
  71 #
  72 # etc.
  73 #
  74 # To accomplish this, subclass list in such a manner that each list element is
  75 # really a two tuple, where the first tuple value is the actual value and the
  76 # second tuple value is a reference to the itemlist node for that value. Users
  77 # only interact with the first tuple values, the actual values, but behind the
  78 # scenes when an element is modified, deleted, inserted, etc, the according
  79 # itemlist nodes are modified, deleted, inserted, etc accordingly. In this
  80 # manner, users can manipulate omdict objects directly through direct list
  81 # manipulation.
  82 #
  83 # Once accomplished, some methods become redundant and should be removed in
  84 # favor of the more intuitive direct value list manipulation. Such redundant
  85 # methods include getlist() (removed in favor of values()?), addlist(), and
  86 # setlist().
  87 #
  88 # With the removal of many of the 'list' methods, think about renaming all
  89 # remaining 'list' methods to 'values' methods, like poplist() -> popvalues(),
  90 # poplistitem() -> popvaluesitem(), etc. This would be an easy switch for most
  91 # methods, but wouldn't fit others so well. For example, iterlists() would
  92 # become itervalues(), a name extremely similar to iterallvalues() but quite
  93 # different in function.
  94 #
  95 
  96 
  97 class omdict(MutableMapping):
  98 
  99     """
 100     Ordered Multivalue Dictionary.
 101 
 102     A multivalue dictionary is a dictionary that can store multiple values per
 103     key. An ordered multivalue dictionary is a multivalue dictionary that
 104     retains the order of insertions and deletions.
 105 
 106     Internally, items are stored in a doubly linked list, self._items. A
 107     dictionary, self._map, is also maintained and stores an ordered list of
 108     linked list node references, one for each value associated with that key.
 109 
 110     Standard dict methods interact with the first value associated with a given
 111     key. This means that omdict retains method parity with dict, and a dict
 112     object can be replaced with an omdict object and all interaction will
 113     behave identically. All dict methods that retain parity with omdict are:
 114 
 115       get(), setdefault(), pop(), popitem(),
 116       clear(), copy(), update(), fromkeys(), len()
 117       __getitem__(), __setitem__(), __delitem__(), __contains__(),
 118       items(), keys(), values(), iteritems(), iterkeys(), itervalues(),
 119 
 120     Optional parameters have been added to some dict methods, but because the
 121     added parameters are optional, existing use remains unaffected. An optional
 122     <key> parameter has been added to these methods:
 123 
 124       items(), values(), iteritems(), itervalues()
 125 
 126     New methods have also been added to omdict. Methods with 'list' in their
 127     name interact with lists of values, and methods with 'all' in their name
 128     interact with all items in the dictionary, including multiple items with
 129     the same key.
 130 
 131     The new omdict methods are:
 132 
 133       load(), size(), reverse(),
 134       getlist(), add(), addlist(), set(), setlist(), setdefaultlist(),
 135       poplist(), popvalue(), popvalues(), popitem(), poplistitem(),
 136       allitems(), allkeys(), allvalues(), lists(), listitems(),
 137       iterallitems(), iterallkeys(), iterallvalues(), iterlists(),
 138         iterlistitems()
 139 
 140     Explanations and examples of the new methods above can be found in the
 141     function comments below and online at
 142 
 143       https://github.com/gruns/orderedmultidict
 144 
 145     Additional omdict information and documentation can also be found at the
 146     above url.
 147     """
 148 
 149     def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
 150         # Doubly linked list of itemnodes. Each itemnode stores a key:value
 151         # item.
 152         self._items = itemlist()
 153 
 154         # Ordered dictionary of keys and itemnode references. Each itemnode
 155         # reference points to one of that keys values.
 156         self._map = odict()
 157 
 158         self.load(*args, **kwargs)
 159 
 160     def load(self, *args, **kwargs):
 161         """
 162         Clear all existing key:value items and import all key:value items from
 163         <mapping>. If multiple values exist for the same key in <mapping>, they
 164         are all be imported.
 165 
 166         Example:
 167           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 168           omd.load([(4,4), (4,44), (5,5)])
 169           omd.allitems() == [(4,4), (4,44), (5,5)]
 170 
 171         Returns: <self>.
 172         """
 173         self.clear()
 174         self.updateall(*args, **kwargs)
 175         return self
 176 
 177     def copy(self):
 178         return self.__class__(self.allitems())
 179 
 180     def clear(self):
 181         self._map.clear()
 182         self._items.clear()
 183 
 184     def size(self):
 185         """
 186         Example:
 187           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 188           omd.size() == 5
 189 
 190         Returns: Total number of items, including multiple items with the same
 191         key.
 192         """
 193         return len(self._items)
 194 
 195     @classmethod
 196     def fromkeys(cls, iterable, value=None):
 197         return cls([(key, value) for key in iterable])
 198 
 199     def has_key(self, key):
 200         return key in self
 201 
 202     def update(self, *args, **kwargs):
 203         self._update_updateall(True, *args, **kwargs)
 204 
 205     def updateall(self, *args, **kwargs):
 206         """
 207         Update this dictionary with the items from <mapping>, replacing
 208         existing key:value items with shared keys before adding new key:value
 209         items.
 210 
 211         Example:
 212           omd = omdict([(1,1), (2,2)])
 213           omd.updateall([(2,'two'), (1,'one'), (2,222), (1,111)])
 214           omd.allitems() == [(1, 'one'), (2, 'two'), (2, 222), (1, 111)]
 215 
 216         Returns: <self>.
 217         """
 218         self._update_updateall(False, *args, **kwargs)
 219         return self
 220 
 221     def _update_updateall(self, replace_at_most_one, *args, **kwargs):
 222         # Bin the items in <args> and <kwargs> into <replacements> or
 223         # <leftovers>. Items in <replacements> are new values to replace old
 224         # values for a given key, and items in <leftovers> are new items to be
 225         # added.
 226         replacements, leftovers = dict(), []
 227         for mapping in chain(args, [kwargs]):
 228             self._bin_update_items(
 229                 self._items_iterator(mapping), replace_at_most_one,
 230                 replacements, leftovers)
 231 
 232         # First, replace existing values for each key.
 233         for key, values in six.iteritems(replacements):
 234             self.setlist(key, values)
 235         # Then, add the leftover items to the end of the list of all items.
 236         for key, value in leftovers:
 237             self.add(key, value)
 238 
 239     def _bin_update_items(self, items, replace_at_most_one,
 240                           replacements, leftovers):
 241         """
 242         <replacements and <leftovers> are modified directly, ala pass by
 243         reference.
 244         """
 245         for key, value in items:
 246             # If there are existing items with key <key> that have yet to be
 247             # marked for replacement, mark that item's value to be replaced by
 248             # <value> by appending it to <replacements>.
 249             if key in self and key not in replacements:
 250                 replacements[key] = [value]
 251             elif (key in self and not replace_at_most_one and
 252                   len(replacements[key]) < len(self.values(key))):
 253                 replacements[key].append(value)
 254             else:
 255                 if replace_at_most_one:
 256                     replacements[key] = [value]
 257                 else:
 258                     leftovers.append((key, value))
 259 
 260     def _items_iterator(self, container):
 261         cont = container
 262         iterator = iter(cont)
 263         if callable_attr(cont, 'iterallitems'):
 264             iterator = cont.iterallitems()
 265         elif callable_attr(cont, 'allitems'):
 266             iterator = iter(cont.allitems())
 267         elif callable_attr(cont, 'iteritems'):
 268             iterator = cont.iteritems()
 269         elif callable_attr(cont, 'items'):
 270             iterator = iter(cont.items())
 271         return iterator
 272 
 273     def get(self, key, default=None):
 274         if key in self:
 275             return self._map[key][0].value
 276         return default
 277 
 278     def getlist(self, key, default=[]):
 279         """
 280         Returns: The list of values for <key> if <key> is in the dictionary,
 281         else <default>. If <default> is not provided, an empty list is
 282         returned.
 283         """
 284         if key in self:
 285             return [node.value for node in self._map[key]]
 286         return default
 287 
 288     def setdefault(self, key, default=None):
 289         if key in self:
 290             return self[key]
 291         self.add(key, default)
 292         return default
 293 
 294     def setdefaultlist(self, key, defaultlist=[None]):
 295         """
 296         Similar to setdefault() except <defaultlist> is a list of values to set
 297         for <key>. If <key> already exists, its existing list of values is
 298         returned.
 299 
 300         If <key> isn't a key and <defaultlist> is an empty list, [], no values
 301         are added for <key> and <key> will not be added as a key.
 302 
 303         Returns: List of <key>'s values if <key> exists in the dictionary,
 304         otherwise <default>.
 305         """
 306         if key in self:
 307             return self.getlist(key)
 308         self.addlist(key, defaultlist)
 309         return defaultlist
 310 
 311     def add(self, key, value=None):
 312         """
 313         Add <value> to the list of values for <key>. If <key> is not in the
 314         dictionary, then <value> is added as the sole value for <key>.
 315 
 316         Example:
 317           omd = omdict()
 318           omd.add(1, 1)  # omd.allitems() == [(1,1)]
 319           omd.add(1, 11) # omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,11)]
 320           omd.add(2, 2)  # omd.allitems() == [(1,1), (1,11), (2,2)]
 321 
 322         Returns: <self>.
 323         """
 324         self._map.setdefault(key, [])
 325         node = self._items.append(key, value)
 326         self._map[key].append(node)
 327         return self
 328 
 329     def addlist(self, key, valuelist=[]):
 330         """
 331         Add the values in <valuelist> to the list of values for <key>. If <key>
 332         is not in the dictionary, the values in <valuelist> become the values
 333         for <key>.
 334 
 335         Example:
 336           omd = omdict([(1,1)])
 337           omd.addlist(1, [11, 111])
 338           omd.allitems() == [(1, 1), (1, 11), (1, 111)]
 339           omd.addlist(2, [2])
 340           omd.allitems() == [(1, 1), (1, 11), (1, 111), (2, 2)]
 341 
 342         Returns: <self>.
 343         """
 344         for value in valuelist:
 345             self.add(key, value)
 346         return self
 347 
 348     def set(self, key, value=None):
 349         """
 350         Sets <key>'s value to <value>. Identical in function to __setitem__().
 351 
 352         Returns: <self>.
 353         """
 354         self[key] = value
 355         return self
 356 
 357     def setlist(self, key, values):
 358         """
 359         Sets <key>'s list of values to <values>. Existing items with key <key>
 360         are first replaced with new values from <values>. Any remaining old
 361         items that haven't been replaced with new values are deleted, and any
 362         new values from <values> that don't have corresponding items with <key>
 363         to replace are appended to the end of the list of all items.
 364 
 365         If values is an empty list, [], <key> is deleted, equivalent in action
 366         to del self[<key>].
 367 
 368         Example:
 369           omd = omdict([(1,1), (2,2)])
 370           omd.setlist(1, [11, 111])
 371           omd.allitems() == [(1,11), (2,2), (1,111)]
 372 
 373           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (2,2), (1,111)])
 374           omd.setlist(1, [None])
 375           omd.allitems() == [(1,None), (2,2)]
 376 
 377           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (2,2), (1,111)])
 378           omd.setlist(1, [])
 379           omd.allitems() == [(2,2)]
 380 
 381         Returns: <self>.
 382         """
 383         if not values and key in self:
 384             self.pop(key)
 385         else:
 386             it = zip_longest(
 387                 list(self._map.get(key, [])), values, fillvalue=_absent)
 388             for node, value in it:
 389                 if node is not _absent and value is not _absent:
 390                     node.value = value
 391                 elif node is _absent:
 392                     self.add(key, value)
 393                 elif value is _absent:
 394                     self._map[key].remove(node)
 395                     self._items.removenode(node)
 396         return self
 397 
 398     def removevalues(self, key, values):
 399         """
 400         Removes all <values> from the values of <key>. If <key> has no
 401         remaining values after removevalues(), the key is popped.
 402 
 403         Example:
 404           omd = omdict([(1, 1), (1, 11), (1, 1), (1, 111)])
 405           omd.removevalues(1, [1, 111])
 406           omd.allitems() == [(1, 11)]
 407 
 408         Returns: <self>.
 409         """
 410         self.setlist(key, [v for v in self.getlist(key) if v not in values])
 411         return self
 412 
 413     def pop(self, key, default=_absent):
 414         if key in self:
 415             return self.poplist(key)[0]
 416         elif key not in self._map and default is not _absent:
 417             return default
 418         raise KeyError(key)
 419 
 420     def poplist(self, key, default=_absent):
 421         """
 422         If <key> is in the dictionary, pop it and return its list of values. If
 423         <key> is not in the dictionary, return <default>. KeyError is raised if
 424         <default> is not provided and <key> is not in the dictionary.
 425 
 426         Example:
 427           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 428           omd.poplist(1) == [1, 11, 111]
 429           omd.allitems() == [(2,2), (3,3)]
 430           omd.poplist(2) == [2]
 431           omd.allitems() == [(3,3)]
 432 
 433         Raises: KeyError if <key> isn't in the dictionary and <default> isn't
 434           provided.
 435         Returns: List of <key>'s values.
 436         """
 437         if key in self:
 438             values = self.getlist(key)
 439             del self._map[key]
 440             for node, nodekey, nodevalue in self._items:
 441                 if nodekey == key:
 442                     self._items.removenode(node)
 443             return values
 444         elif key not in self._map and default is not _absent:
 445             return default
 446         raise KeyError(key)
 447 
 448     def popvalue(self, key, value=_absent, default=_absent, last=True):
 449         """
 450         If <value> is provided, pops the first or last (key,value) item in the
 451         dictionary if <key> is in the dictionary.
 452 
 453         If <value> is not provided, pops the first or last value for <key> if
 454         <key> is in the dictionary.
 455 
 456         If <key> no longer has any values after a popvalue() call, <key> is
 457         removed from the dictionary. If <key> isn't in the dictionary and
 458         <default> was provided, return default. KeyError is raised if <default>
 459         is not provided and <key> is not in the dictionary. ValueError is
 460         raised if <value> is provided but isn't a value for <key>.
 461 
 462         Example:
 463           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3), (2,22)])
 464           omd.popvalue(1) == 111
 465           omd.allitems() == [(1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3), (2,22)]
 466           omd.popvalue(1, last=False) == 1
 467           omd.allitems() == [(1,11), (2,2), (3,3), (2,22)]
 468           omd.popvalue(2, 2) == 2
 469           omd.allitems() == [(1,11), (3,3), (2,22)]
 470           omd.popvalue(1, 11) == 11
 471           omd.allitems() == [(3,3), (2,22)]
 472           omd.popvalue('not a key', default='sup') == 'sup'
 473 
 474         Params:
 475           last: Boolean whether to return <key>'s first value (<last> is False)
 476             or last value (<last> is True).
 477         Raises:
 478           KeyError if <key> isn't in the dictionary and <default> isn't
 479             provided.
 480           ValueError if <value> isn't a value for <key>.
 481         Returns: The first or last of <key>'s values.
 482         """
 483         def pop_node_with_index(key, index):
 484             node = self._map[key].pop(index)
 485             if not self._map[key]:
 486                 del self._map[key]
 487             self._items.removenode(node)
 488             return node
 489 
 490         if key in self:
 491             if value is not _absent:
 492                 if last:
 493                     pos = self.values(key)[::-1].index(value)
 494                 else:
 495                     pos = self.values(key).index(value)
 496                 if pos == -1:
 497                     raise ValueError(value)
 498                 else:
 499                     index = (len(self.values(key)) - 1 - pos) if last else pos
 500                     return pop_node_with_index(key, index).value
 501             else:
 502                 return pop_node_with_index(key, -1 if last else 0).value
 503         elif key not in self._map and default is not _absent:
 504             return default
 505         raise KeyError(key)
 506 
 507     def popitem(self, fromall=False, last=True):
 508         """
 509         Pop and return a key:value item.
 510 
 511         If <fromall> is False, items()[0] is popped if <last> is False or
 512         items()[-1] is popped if <last> is True. All remaining items with the
 513         same key are removed.
 514 
 515         If <fromall> is True, allitems()[0] is popped if <last> is False or
 516         allitems()[-1] is popped if <last> is True. Any remaining items with
 517         the same key remain.
 518 
 519         Example:
 520           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 521           omd.popitem() == (3,3)
 522           omd.popitem(fromall=False, last=False) == (1,1)
 523           omd.popitem(fromall=False, last=False) == (2,2)
 524 
 525           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 526           omd.popitem(fromall=True, last=False) == (1,1)
 527           omd.popitem(fromall=True, last=False) == (1,11)
 528           omd.popitem(fromall=True, last=True) == (3,3)
 529           omd.popitem(fromall=True, last=False) == (1,111)
 530 
 531         Params:
 532           fromall: Whether to pop an item from items() (<fromall> is True) or
 533             allitems() (<fromall> is False).
 534           last: Boolean whether to pop the first item or last item of items()
 535             or allitems().
 536         Raises: KeyError if the dictionary is empty.
 537         Returns: The first or last item from item() or allitem().
 538         """
 539         if not self._items:
 540             raise KeyError('popitem(): %s is empty' % self.__class__.__name__)
 541 
 542         if fromall:
 543             node = self._items[-1 if last else 0]
 544             key = node.key
 545             return key, self.popvalue(key, last=last)
 546         else:
 547             key = list(self._map.keys())[-1 if last else 0]
 548             return key, self.pop(key)
 549 
 550     def poplistitem(self, last=True):
 551         """
 552         Pop and return a key:valuelist item comprised of a key and that key's
 553         list of values. If <last> is False, a key:valuelist item comprised of
 554         keys()[0] and its list of values is popped and returned. If <last> is
 555         True, a key:valuelist item comprised of keys()[-1] and its list of
 556         values is popped and returned.
 557 
 558         Example:
 559           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 560           omd.poplistitem(last=True) == (3,[3])
 561           omd.poplistitem(last=False) == (1,[1,11,111])
 562 
 563         Params:
 564           last: Boolean whether to pop the first or last key and its associated
 565             list of values.
 566         Raises: KeyError if the dictionary is empty.
 567         Returns: A two-tuple comprised of the first or last key and its
 568           associated list of values.
 569         """
 570         if not self._items:
 571             s = 'poplistitem(): %s is empty' % self.__class__.__name__
 572             raise KeyError(s)
 573 
 574         key = self.keys()[-1 if last else 0]
 575         return key, self.poplist(key)
 576 
 577     def items(self, key=_absent):
 578         """
 579         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and not in the dictionary.
 580         Returns: List created from iteritems(<key>). Only items with key <key>
 581           are returned if <key> is provided and is a dictionary key.
 582         """
 583         return list(self.iteritems(key))
 584 
 585     def keys(self):
 586         return list(self.iterkeys())
 587 
 588     def values(self, key=_absent):
 589         """
 590         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and not in the dictionary.
 591         Returns: List created from itervalues(<key>).If <key> is provided and
 592           is a dictionary key, only values of items with key <key> are
 593           returned.
 594         """
 595         if key is not _absent and key in self._map:
 596             return self.getlist(key)
 597         return list(self.itervalues())
 598 
 599     def lists(self):
 600         """
 601         Returns: List created from iterlists().
 602         """
 603         return list(self.iterlists())
 604 
 605     def listitems(self):
 606         """
 607         Returns: List created from iterlistitems().
 608         """
 609         return list(self.iterlistitems())
 610 
 611     def iteritems(self, key=_absent):
 612         """
 613         Parity with dict.iteritems() except the optional <key> parameter has
 614         been added. If <key> is provided, only items with the provided key are
 615         iterated over. KeyError is raised if <key> is provided and not in the
 616         dictionary.
 617 
 618         Example:
 619           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 620           omd.iteritems(1) -> (1,1) -> (1,11) -> (1,111)
 621           omd.iteritems() -> (1,1) -> (2,2) -> (3,3)
 622 
 623         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and not in the dictionary.
 624         Returns: An iterator over the items() of the dictionary, or only items
 625           with the key <key> if <key> is provided.
 626         """
 627         if key is not _absent:
 628             if key in self:
 629                 items = [(node.key, node.value) for node in self._map[key]]
 630                 return iter(items)
 631             raise KeyError(key)
 632         items = six.iteritems(self._map)
 633         return iter((key, nodes[0].value) for (key, nodes) in items)
 634 
 635     def iterkeys(self):
 636         return six.iterkeys(self._map)
 637 
 638     def itervalues(self, key=_absent):
 639         """
 640         Parity with dict.itervalues() except the optional <key> parameter has
 641         been added. If <key> is provided, only values from items with the
 642         provided key are iterated over. KeyError is raised if <key> is provided
 643         and not in the dictionary.
 644 
 645         Example:
 646           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 647           omd.itervalues(1) -> 1 -> 11 -> 111
 648           omd.itervalues() -> 1 -> 11 -> 111 -> 2 -> 3
 649 
 650         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and isn't in the dictionary.
 651         Returns: An iterator over the values() of the dictionary, or only the
 652           values of key <key> if <key> is provided.
 653         """
 654         if key is not _absent:
 655             if key in self:
 656                 return iter([node.value for node in self._map[key]])
 657             raise KeyError(key)
 658         return iter([nodes[0].value for nodes in six.itervalues(self._map)])
 659 
 660     def allitems(self, key=_absent):
 661         '''
 662         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and not in the dictionary.
 663         Returns: List created from iterallitems(<key>).
 664         '''
 665         return list(self.iterallitems(key))
 666 
 667     def allkeys(self):
 668         '''
 669         Example:
 670           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 671           omd.allkeys() == [1,1,1,2,3]
 672 
 673         Returns: List created from iterallkeys().
 674         '''
 675         return list(self.iterallkeys())
 676 
 677     def allvalues(self, key=_absent):
 678         '''
 679         Example:
 680           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 681           omd.allvalues() == [1,11,111,2,3]
 682           omd.allvalues(1) == [1,11,111]
 683 
 684         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and not in the dictionary.
 685         Returns: List created from iterallvalues(<key>).
 686         '''
 687         return list(self.iterallvalues(key))
 688 
 689     def iterallitems(self, key=_absent):
 690         '''
 691         Example:
 692           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 693           omd.iterallitems() == (1,1) -> (1,11) -> (1,111) -> (2,2) -> (3,3)
 694           omd.iterallitems(1) == (1,1) -> (1,11) -> (1,111)
 695 
 696         Raises: KeyError if <key> is provided and not in the dictionary.
 697         Returns: An iterator over every item in the diciontary. If <key> is
 698           provided, only items with the key <key> are iterated over.
 699         '''
 700         if key is not _absent:
 701             # Raises KeyError if <key> is not in self._map.
 702             return self.iteritems(key)
 703         return self._items.iteritems()
 704 
 705     def iterallkeys(self):
 706         '''
 707         Example:
 708           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 709           omd.iterallkeys() == 1 -> 1 -> 1 -> 2 -> 3
 710 
 711         Returns: An iterator over the keys of every item in the dictionary.
 712         '''
 713         return self._items.iterkeys()
 714 
 715     def iterallvalues(self, key=_absent):
 716         '''
 717         Example:
 718           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 719           omd.iterallvalues() == 1 -> 11 -> 111 -> 2 -> 3
 720 
 721         Returns: An iterator over the values of every item in the dictionary.
 722         '''
 723         if key is not _absent:
 724             if key in self:
 725                 return iter(self.getlist(key))
 726             raise KeyError(key)
 727         return self._items.itervalues()
 728 
 729     def iterlists(self):
 730         '''
 731         Example:
 732           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 733           omd.iterlists() -> [1,11,111] -> [2] -> [3]
 734 
 735         Returns: An iterator over the list comprised of the lists of values for
 736         each key.
 737         '''
 738         return map(lambda key: self.getlist(key), self)
 739 
 740     def iterlistitems(self):
 741         """
 742         Example:
 743           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 744           omd.iterlistitems() -> (1,[1,11,111]) -> (2,[2]) -> (3,[3])
 745 
 746         Returns: An iterator over the list of key:valuelist items.
 747         """
 748         return map(lambda key: (key, self.getlist(key)), self)
 749 
 750     def reverse(self):
 751         """
 752         Reverse the order of all items in the dictionary.
 753 
 754         Example:
 755           omd = omdict([(1,1), (1,11), (1,111), (2,2), (3,3)])
 756           omd.reverse()
 757           omd.allitems() == [(3,3), (2,2), (1,111), (1,11), (1,1)]
 758 
 759         Returns: <self>.
 760         """
 761         for key in six.iterkeys(self._map):
 762             self._map[key].reverse()
 763         self._items.reverse()
 764         return self
 765 
 766     def __eq__(self, other):
 767         if callable_attr(other, 'iterallitems'):
 768             myiter, otheriter = self.iterallitems(), other.iterallitems()
 769             for i1, i2 in zip_longest(myiter, otheriter, fillvalue=_absent):
 770                 if i1 != i2 or i1 is _absent or i2 is _absent:
 771                     return False
 772         elif not hasattr(other, '__len__') or not hasattr(other, _items_attr):
 773             return False
 774         # Ignore order so we can compare ordered omdicts with unordered dicts.
 775         else:
 776             if len(self) != len(other):
 777                 return False
 778             for key, value in six.iteritems(other):
 779                 if self.get(key, _absent) != value:
 780                     return False
 781         return True
 782 
 783     def __ne__(self, other):
 784         return not self.__eq__(other)
 785 
 786     def __len__(self):
 787         return len(self._map)
 788 
 789     def __iter__(self):
 790         for key in self.iterkeys():
 791             yield key
 792 
 793     def __contains__(self, key):
 794         return key in self._map
 795 
 796     def __getitem__(self, key):
 797         if key in self:
 798             return self.get(key)
 799         raise KeyError(key)
 800 
 801     def __setitem__(self, key, value):
 802         self.setlist(key, [value])
 803 
 804     def __delitem__(self, key):
 805         return self.pop(key)
 806 
 807     def __nonzero__(self):
 808         return bool(self._map)
 809 
 810     def __str__(self):
 811         return '{%s}' % ', '.join(
 812             map(lambda p: '%r: %r' % (p[0], p[1]), self.iterallitems()))
 813 
 814     def __repr__(self):
 815         return '%s(%s)' % (self.__class__.__name__, self.allitems())
 816 
 817     def __or__(self, other):
 818         return self.__class__(chain(_get_items(self), _get_items(other)))
 819 
 820     def __ior__(self, other):
 821         for k, v in _get_items(other):
 822             self.add(k, value=v)
 823         return self

 825 
 826 def _get_items(mapping):
 827     """Find item iterator for an object."""
 828     names = ('iterallitems', 'allitems', 'iteritems', 'items')
 829     exist = (n for n in names if callable_attr(mapping, n))
 830     for a in exist:
 831         return getattr(mapping, a)()
 832     raise TypeError(
 833         "Object {} has no compatible items interface.".format(mapping))
